OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax     F428A1720143661
OL,3,CAn encounter with a former gang member
OL,4,Cwho has 'seen people get stabbed'
OL,6,FHe tells us he's no longer involved in
OL,7,Fa gang, but the way he talks, it feels
OL,8,Flike he still has allegiances. He says
OL,9,Fhe needs his identity protecting,
OL,10,Fbecause just speaking to us could put
OL,11,Fhim in danger.
OL,13,FI ask him how he ended up in a gang.
OL,14,FHe says: "It's just your mates innit.
OL,15,FI wouldn't really call it a gang, but
OL,16,Fthat's what other people see. They see
OL,17,Fwor as a gang."
OL,19,FFor a group of mates, it must have
OL,20,Fbeen difficult to leave the fold, I
OL,21,Fask. He agrees.
OL,1,W~k4~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}        G4/13
OL,2,W/*%+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,,,,,,
